title: ‘An epidemic’: Five people set ablaze on public transport in a month
description: Filmmaker Ami Horowitz is astounded that five people have been set on fire while riding public transport in New York and Chicago in the last month.   “This idea of setting people ablaze on our cities' transport system, this is not an isolated incident at all,” Mr Horowitz told Sky News host Rita Panahi.  “Five people in Chicago and New York alone were set on fire.  “This is an epidemic, this is unbelievable.”

title: Trump designates chapters of the Muslim Brotherhood as a terrorist organisation
description: Filmmaker Ami Horowitz gives kudos to US President Donald Trump for signing an executive order earlier today that designates chapters of the Muslim Brotherhood as a foreign terrorist organisation.  The Muslim Brotherhood is a Sunni Islamist organisation founded in Egypt in 1928.  The White House argues the designation will help the US combat the group's transnational network, which is said to fuel terrorism against US interests and allies in the Middle East.   “It’s one of the most dangerous organisations that exists,” Mr Horowitz told Sky News host Rita Panahi.  “Kudos to the President for designating them and pushing this for years as a terrorist organisation.  “Their main point of business is terror.”

title: ‘We’re nowhere near the end’: Trump’s 28-point peace plan for Ukraine analysed by Nigel Farage
description: Reform UK Leader Nigel Farage analyses US President Donald Trump’s 28-point plan for peace in Ukraine.  “The 28-point plan that was leaked … I came out and said it was unacceptable, you can’t tell a sovereign country how big its army should be,” Mr Farage told Sky News host Paul Murray.  “It’s a negotiation, it goes in stages … everybody forgets that wars only end in one or two ways, they either end in annihilation, or they end in a negotiated settlement.”

title: ‘The major issue’: Inflation figures tipped to rise
description: Sky News host Paul Murray highlights how inflation figures are tipped to rise under the Labor government and Australia’s cost of living crisis.

title: Ukraine will have to ‘trade some land’ for peace with Russia
description: Strategic Analysis Australia Director Peter Jennings says, unfortunately, Ukraine will have to “trade some land for peace” with Russia in the 19-point draft plan.  “What they need to do now is to hold out for as much as they can possibly get in terms of NATO, American and European military support,” Mr Jennings told Sky News host Sharri Markson.  “Everyone accepts the Ukrainian concern that if Russia is allowed to get away with too much, they'll simply invade again.  “I think Trump will understand that.”

title: Canberra’s ‘over the top approach’ to China visit
description: Strategic Analysis Australia Director Peter Jennings discusses the “over the top approach” to the Chinese delegation visiting Parliament House and sparking security fears.  “The security that's been put around the place is just astonishing … far more than I have seen for visiting American presidents,” Mr Jennings told Sky News host Sharri Markson.  “It reflects the type of differential approach to dealing with China.”

title: Labor uses Trump’s 2020 election loss to justify FOI crackdown
description: On tonight’s episode of Paul Murray Live, Sky News host Paul Murray discusses Labor’s FOI crackdown, inflation tipped to rise, US politics and more.

title: Former Labor councillor claims Pauline Hanson’s movie ban was a ‘brilliant PR distraction’
description: Former Labor councillor Linda Scott analyses One Nation Leader Pauline Hanson’s movie screening being banned by parliament just as the senator was censured over her burqa stunt.  “I do think this is a brilliant PR distraction by One Nation,” Ms Scott told Sky News host Paul Murray.  “To take away from the fact she’s been removed from the One Nation brand.”

title: Baffling Indigenous policy calls for ‘culturally respectful’ space exploration
description: Sky News host Freya Leach highlights how an “interstellar” Indigenous policy calls for ‘culturally respectful and environmentally responsible space exploration’.

title: RBA implements ‘wellbeing days’ amid national productivity growth warnings
description: Sky News host James Macpherson highlights how the Reserve Bank of Australia have been given eight ‘wellbeing days’ which comes amid national productivity warnings.  “It’s kind of a modern miracle, it is a day off work where you don’t have to explain yourself at all,” Mr Macpherson said.  “Nothing says fiscal responsibility like the RBA paying staff to do absolutely anything, or nothing at all.”

title: Trump admin instructs Australian embassy to collect immigrant crime data
description: Sky News host James Macpherson highlights how the Trump administration has told their Australian embassy to collate crimes committed by migrants.  “Curiously they have not told local governments they are doing this,” Mr Macpherson said.  “They have just instructed their officials to do it.”

title: ‘Too offensive’: UK council cancels flag exhibition representing multicultural Britain
description: Sky News host Freya Leach highlights how a UK council has cancelled an artist’s Union flag exhibition.

title: Pauline Hanson shares steak dinner with Barnaby Joyce
description: Sky News host Steve Price reacts to One Nation Leader Pauline Hanson and former deputy prime minister Barnaby Joyce sharing a steak dinner together.

title: Fake accounts exposed by X found to be taking Gaza donations
description: Sky News host Sharri Markson reacts to the “so-called” accounts claiming to be posting from Gaza are not from there at all as exposed by X’s new location feature.  Ms Markson sat down with Israeli Deputy Foreign Minister Sharren Haskel to go over the fake accounts.  The new feature has exposed many claiming to be part of Gaza as fake.

title: ‘Run out of your money’: Labor launches ‘austerity drive’
description: Sky News host Andrew Bolt says Labor launching an austerity drive is a “joke”.  Mr Bolt said the government has “run out of your money”.  Labor has hired an extra 38,000 public servants in just three years.
